Yeah, right, a letter-writing campaign to MS competitors. That'll do the
trick. Where's my fountain pen?

Seriously, though, Microsoft has the desktop business-productivity market
dominated beyond hope, but that generation of computers is nearing its end
anyway. The next stage is up for grabs: the mobile networked
document-centered microkernel object-oriented multiplatform software of
tomorrow---Workplace OS, Taligent, etc.

MS looms large only because of its wobbly stilts: the requirement that
users stick with a single OS and processor type, and the need to be
backwards-compatible with earlier versions of software. With both those
selling points eliminated by the introduction of more flexible computer
architectures, people might actually---*gasp!*---start choosing their
software on the basis of quality and features. I think we'd all agree that
on a level playing field, Microsoft products wouldn't be nearly as
successful as they are right now. So there IS hope, my friends...

